lead_paragraph: 9 P.M. (Oxygen) PRIDE & PREJUDICE (2005) Keira Knightley, in an Oscar-nominated role, stars as Elizabeth Bennet in Joe Wright’s adaptation of the Jane Austen novel about five sisters whose mother (Brenda Blethyn) is desperate to marry them off to men of means. Rosamund Pike is Jane, Elizabeth’s older sister and the belle of the ball. “But because Ms. Knightley is, in a word, a knockout, the balance has shifted,” Stephen Holden wrote in The New York Times. “Her radiance so suffuses the film that it’s foolish to imagine Elizabeth would be anyone’s second choice.” Once viewers accept this, the movie “gathers you up on its white horse and gallops off into the sunset,” he added. “In its final minutes it makes you believe in true love, the union of soul mates, happily ever after and all the other stuff a romantic comedy promises but so seldom delivers.”

abstract: This documentary details the life and career of Tucker, a hobnobbing 20th-century jazz singer known for her big voice.
snippet: This documentary details the life and career of Tucker, a hobnobbing 20th-century jazz singer known for her big voice.
lead_paragraph: If you close your eyes and randomly select a page from the autobiography of the singer Sophie Tucker, you may well end up reading a throwaway anecdote like this: “Queen Marie of Romania came to Chicago during our run there. We all hoped she would come to see the show, and an invitation was sent to Her Majesty. But she sent a gracious letter of apology, and we had to be content that night with Al Capone and a party of 20.” Flip a few more pages, and there’s this: “Will I ever forget the hamburger dinner I cooked for Fanny Brice and Aunt Jemima!”

abstract: Donald J. Trump reported earnings of at least $380 million over the last 18 months and assets of at least $1.4 billion in his financial disclosure filing with the Federal Election Commission.
snippet: Donald J. Trump reported earnings of at least $380 million over the last 18 months and assets of at least $1.4 billion in his financial disclosure filing with the Federal Election Commission.
lead_paragraph: Donald J. Trump earned just $14,222 in salary. He owes at least $265 million in debt. He is paid about $250,000 per speech. And he received $110,000 from a pension with the Screen Actors Guild.

abstract: Donald Trump’s latest fit of pique, about Senator John McCain’s reputation as a war hero, exposed the biggest vulnerability of Mr. Trump’s campaign for president.
snippet: Donald Trump’s latest fit of pique, about Senator John McCain’s reputation as a war hero, exposed the biggest vulnerability of Mr. Trump’s campaign for president.
lead_paragraph: In what passes for normal inside Donald J. Trump’s unorthodox campaign for president, he flew from Arkansas to Iowa on his Trump-emblazoned jet on Friday, arrived the next morning at a candidate forum without any prepared remarks and, wearing a bright red tie that evoked his days on “The Apprentice,” told the world exactly what he thought about Senator John McCain’s reputation as a war hero.

abstract: Erasing student loans requires proof that paying the debt would cause “undue hardship,” and some judges think the rigid standard should be reconsidered.
snippet: Erasing student loans requires proof that paying the debt would cause “undue hardship,” and some judges think the rigid standard should be reconsidered.
lead_paragraph: On a typical day in her last job, Janet Roth left home at 4 a.m. each day and drove 40 miles to a tax preparation office in Glendale, Ariz. When she finally got back home, she had less than an hour before starting her 6 p.m. shift decorating cakes at Walmart. She worked until midnight, giving her just a few hours to sleep before starting all over again.

abstract: Few places on Earth are as free from legal oversight as the high seas. One ship has been among the most persistent offenders.
snippet: Few places on Earth are as free from legal oversight as the high seas. One ship has been among the most persistent offenders.
lead_paragraph: CHIOS, Greece — The rickety raft made of empty oil drums and a wooden tabletop rolled and pitched with the waves while tied to the side of the Dona Liberta, a 370-foot cargo ship anchored far from land in the Atlantic Ocean off West Africa.

abstract: Three views of impacts, options and responsibilities as humanity’s growth spurt nudge’s Earth’s operating systems.
snippet: Three views of impacts, options and responsibilities as humanity’s growth spurt nudge’s Earth’s operating systems.
lead_paragraph: Last month, the Breakthrough Institute, a scrappy research organization focused on the interface of environment, energy, technology and economics, organized a spirited dialogue around its “Ecomodernist Manifesto” — an 18-author essay arguing that “knowledge and technology, applied with wisdom, might allow for a good, or even great, Anthropocene.”

lead_paragraph: 1 A.M. (FX Movie Channel) CHASING MAVERICKS (2012) Rick Hesson (Gerard Butler), a surfer in Santa Cruz nicknamed Frosty, teaches Jay Moriarity (Jonny Weston), a legend in the making, the way of the waves — specifically, the monster crushers in Northern California on a break known as Mavericks. Curtis Hanson and Michael Apted shared the directing duties on this film, based on a true story that begins in 1987 and is lent authenticity by the real surfers Greg Long, Peter Mel and Zach Wormhoudt. “When the movie works, its buoyancy can be infectious and persuasive, particularly in the surfing scenes and in the mesmerizing shots of the heaving, churning ocean and waves,” Manohla Dargis wrote in The New York Times. The film, she added, “invites you to gaze into this watery abyss, to ponder its mysteries as well as those of the swimmer whose image brackets the movie and evokes John F. Kennedy’s observation: ‘We are tied to the ocean. And when we go back to the sea, whether it is to sail or to watch, we are going back from whence we came.’ ”

lead_paragraph: 9 P.M. (13) HARPER LEE: AMERICAN MASTERS In honor of the release of Ms. Lee’s novel “Go Set a Watchman” on Tuesday, Mary McDonagh Murphy — who was able to read an advance copy — has updated her 2011 documentary, “Hey, Boo: Harper Lee and ‘To Kill a Mockingbird.’ ” (Above, Ms. Lee with Gregory Peck at the movie’s premiere in 1962.) Ms. Murphy will also post on Twitter (#HarperLeePBS) during the broadcast. “It gives the fascinating history of how the book came to be, which involved Truman Capote, a perceptive editor and an act of generosity that helped give Ms. Lee, the novel’s author, the time she needed to write,” Neil Genzlinger wrote in The New York Times of the original documentary, adding that the best moments come from other authors, who read passages and talk about the book’s impact on their work. “But just when this is beginning to seem like pandering,” he added, Oprah Winfrey “gives the most eloquent reading of all, of the scene in which Atticus leaves the courtroom after the pivotal verdict.” The broadcast is part of “Thirteen Days of Harper Lee,” an event featuring videos, book discussions and a link to “Essential Longform: The Best Harper Lee Reads,” assembled by the New York Public Library. (thirteen.org)
